Every new birth that takes place in our world is a beautiful sign of divinity.

It’s a beautiful sign of God interacting with humankind to say:

I want to create life.

I want to put something beautiful into the world that has all the signs of My image baked into who they are.

When we as humans start to mess with that and think that we have a better way to perfect children, all of these ideologies start to come into play.

Instead of trusting God’s perfect design we start to manipulate and think we know what’s better.

Enjoy the discussion from Episode Two “Build The Parallel” everywhere podcasts are streamed.

The enemy wants us divided

A few questions I’m asking myself and desire to discuss with others are these:

1. Who can I trust for credible information in an age where information is controlled, manipulated or mediated by large institutions that may not have my best interest in mind?

2. How is Christian moral leadership best exercised during a time of confusion?

3. Where can those I lead discuss controversial, cultural issues without creating more division?

4. What parallel structures can the church and Christian institutions create that support both the flourishing of the Church and their neighbors?

…wait till the end to hear number 5!

Hear the rest of the discussion in Episode 3 “My Letter to Church Leaders” from my new podcast UnderCurrent anywhere podcasts can be streamed.

You can download my letter at gabelyons.com/letter

How far are we willing to go for the sake of ‘convenience’? 

How will the merging of technology, currency, biometrics and surveillance change how we live? 

The coming technocracy is closer than you think—in fact, you are helping build it.

Listen to my latest episode of Undercurrent ‘Understanding The Technocracy’ for my take.

How God saw fit for Pastor Tim Keller to take me under his wing early in my career is incredible—and humbling. 
 
We were born in different generations, yet united in faith, and I always found him to be as principled in private as we all experienced in public. 
 
One firsthand experience was in 2012 in our time preparing for a private meeting in the Oval Office. Our goal was to urge President Obama to be a unifier, not a divider, even as he offered his full support to make same-sex marriage accepted and legal. We hoped Obama would affirm that people of faith who disagreed with this new cultural norm would still have the freedom to exercise their beliefs in their daily lives. That we could all get along, despite our deepest differences. 
 
No one would know for years that the meeting took place—Tim wasn’t political, he was principled. I sat there as he so eloquently articulated to a sitting U.S. President, why the historic, Biblical view of marriage and sexuality would always be a presence in our public square. Tim was succinct, well-reasoned and persuasive. 
 
While our discussions that day didn’t dislodge an accelerating cultural moment, it was representative of the dozens of private meetings and collaborations Tim invested in with me and others. Not for his benefit, but to help strengthen pastors and Christian leaders who had beautiful contributions to bring into the public square, especially when articulated with contextual clarity and bold Gospel witness. 
 
Rebekah and I are ever thankful for the mentorship and faithful legacy of our friend and brother in Christ, Tim Keller. He helped us ground the work of Q Ideas (now THINQ Media) from the start. Today and always, we’ll celebrate his extraordinary life.

It’s hard to have a good conversation these days, especially about faith. 

Even when two people pretty much agree, honest interaction seems elusive. 

But being friends across differences is hard, and cultivating good conversations is the rocky, uphill climb that leads there. 

Good conversations demand active listening, mental and emotional engagement, openness to the possibility that we’re wrong, and empathy to see the situation from the other person’s point of view. 

Good conversations, our best hope for peace in conflicted relationships, are on the endangered species list. 

Our research shows that having meaningful conversations is increasingly difficult for many of us. 

This is true not only on an individual level but also society-wide. 

Why is a good conversation so difficult to find these days? 

Read more in Good Faith to find out- available at gabelyons.com/books link in bio #goodfaith #faith #goodconversation

How do you think social media has changed our capacity for healthy, effective, good conversations about our differences? 

According to Barna research, most people believe these digital tools have made meaningful dialogue and deep connection more difficult. 

In fact, 61 percent of adults say they believe social media has made people less social, less capable of deep friendships and strong connections. 

Furthermore, Americans are twice as likely today to say they are lonely compared to ten years ago. 

Social media doesn’t always make us more social. 

How can we have conversations that matter on important issues between people and between groups of people? 

How can we believe with conviction and courage while reknitting social and spiritual bonds? 

To read more checkout Good Faith at the link in my bio #goodfaith #faith #goodconversations

Our culture lacks a shared center. 

The bottom has dropped out. 

There is no center any longer. 

There is a giant vacuum in the middle of our moral and spiritual lives.

It may not be a coordinated effort, but
let’s not be naïve: those with a different worldview would love to fill the cultural vacuum with their notions of what is true.

As Christianity has been ushered out of our social structures and off the cultural main stage, it has left a vacuum in its place. 

And the broader culture is trying to fill the void.

5 steps to thinking critically.

We are experiencing a crisis of trust. 

Citizens no longer know where to go or who to listen to for credible information. 

Misinformation, polarization and self-censorship are a few of the consequences when belief begins to deteriorate. 

We need to learn how to think critically for ourselves:

1. Ask questions
2. Gather information
3. Filter through the lens of wisdom
4. Draw a conclusion
5. Encourage others to think critically in community

For more go to gabelyons.com/undercurrent

“I think we should treat these young people the same way we treat any other young person who’s struggling with mental health issues. We should be caring and loving to them and we should get them help, and we should pay attention to the root causes of why they’re feeling the way that they’re feeling.”

The credibility that comes with hearing it in her own words, carries more weight than my own.

Helena Kerschner, a former transgender man, joined the THINQ stage to discuss the social impacts of the transgender movement and how we can help and support those around us (especially our kids) who may be dealing with questions of identity.

To watch the whole conversation check out the link in my bio.

Faithfulness is not easy. 

Traveling this new landscape will require an unshakeable commitment to knowing how the world and human beings were designed to operate. 

But perhaps even more important, it will require an unshakeable commitment to love. 

Love that helps our families navigate the many difficult conversations that lie ahead, and love that speaks and acts with respect for those with whom we disagree. 

Being faithful often demands that we express ideas that conflict with the majority culture’s claims, concerns, and commitments. 

What Christians believe about sin, human purpose, identity, and ultimate meaning is at odds with the beliefs of many others. 

But we can’t stay quiet.

A reminder as we celebrate freedom this week.

Governments will fall, leaders will fail us, but God is constant and will always prevail.

We submit to those he has placed in authority over us, all the while remembering our superior obligation to the divine monarchy of God.

There is freedom found in his truth.

A freedom greater than any this world has to offer.

(Watch the whole conversation with William B. Allen at the link in my bio)

One nation.

Under God.

Indivisible.

With liberty and justice for all.

🇺🇸

(Watch the full conversation with William B. Allen at the link in my bio.)

The freedom to practice a faith different from the country's leader, to associate with others who share our convictions, to fund efforts that align with our beliefs about human flourishing, and not to participate in practices that violate our conscience are fundamental, inalienable rights.

These are bedrock American ideas, adopted as the law of the land less than ten years after the Revolutionary War was won.

“The Religion then of every man must be left to the conviction and conscience of every man; and it is the right of every man to exercise it as these may dictate. This right is in its nature an unalienable right." - James Madison

The America we live in today may not look like what it did in James Madison’s time, but our fundamental rights and freedoms still stand.

And we must continue to speak up to keep it that way.

“In contemporary society, our adversary (the devil) majors in three things: noise, hurry, and crowds. If he can keep us engaged in ‘muchness’ and ‘manyness’ he will rest satisfied.” - Richard Foster

Do we make productivity an idol?

What experiences or relationships are we missing in the midst of our ‘efficiency’?

We must begin to retrain our minds and imagination to become people who live to love God- not simply live to be productive.

When it comes to conversations about beliefs, morals, and faith, Christians have often emphasized the importance of being winsome and engaging. 

We’ll make the argument, however, that it’s no longer sufficient for Christians to be winsome. 

Being winsome is not bad. It’s good. 

But aiming for niceness as our ultimate goal can give us a false sense of making a difference in people’s lives. 

More and more people think the Christian community is completely out of step with the times. 

These people might listen for entertainment’s sake, but Christians have little chance of breaking through to real understanding. 

Now, this is not an excuse to be less kind. 

Far from it. 

Rather, it’s an invitation for Christians to rethink our manner of being “in the world but not of it.”

We don’t tell people what to think- we simply ask them to think.

Jesus did this so well in the manner of asking questions.

In a world of chaos, confusion, and emotivism where our emotions are starting to drive what we believe is true or false- we are going to need to ask people to think. 

We do this by asking good questions.

Advancing the kingdom takes shape in the tangible, everyday expression of our lives. 

Consider Brian and Julie Mavis, who created a nation-wide effort for Christians to take the lead in the foster care movement. 

Or take Dan Cooper, who created an index fund built on the character of CEOs reshaping Wall Street values. 

Look at David Bailey, who’s leading racial reconciliation efforts through education and music. 

It’s not just them, either. It’s the myriad unknown leaders — nurses, engineers, paralegals, stay-at-home moms — who are shaping a kingdom-focused future.

“Evil counts on isolating us to do it’s work.”

Although technology brings convenience, it can also encourage us into isolation.

We must be intentional about our connections with others, and living lives in accountability and relations to those around us just as God has created us to do.

As Christians we believe that every human life-in all its forms, at every stage--matters.

We are called to protect life as God's good gift to us. 

Jesus had a pretty extreme view of how much we should value life.

He taught that we are to love our neighbors, even when doing so could endanger our lives. "There is no greater love than to lay down one's life for one's friends"
(John 15:13).

We must push back against a culture that views life as disposable. 

And our value of life must be holistic. 

We must focus not only on protecting life prior to birth but also on nurturing children after they are born. 

This means supporting mothers-to-be who are scared, ashamed, and uncertain.

This also means adding to the increasing number of adoptive and foster families in our churches.

Christianity is not just for Sunday morning when we feel like it or weeknight Bible study when we don't have anything better to do-and it's certainly not just for making us feel good about ourselves. 

The sooner we renounce the me-me-me belief, the sooner we can offer others a way out of their own self-centeredness.

This is the church at its best: healing sinners of our self-inflicted wounds so we can become healers too.

This won't be easy. 

Decoupling from the culture's narrative can happen only when communities of faith adopt a new way of life, one rooted in Scripture. 

This will, indeed, be counter-cultural. 

But the Christian faith has a pretty good track record when Christians stick to the basics.

This clip is from 2020 but I believe is still so relevant.

Our younger generation is struggling.

Struggling to find hope, struggling to feel purpose.

Satan will stop at nothing to attack with his lies.

We must protect, love, teach, and equip this next generation.

We must pour into them the hope we have in Jesus, and the purpose found in living life for him.

We must cover them in prayer, and pray alongside
them.

The enemy comes to steal, kill, and destroy, but Jesus has come, that we may have life, and have it to the full.

There’s a generation we are going to lose, not because we decided to stick with our convictions, but because we decided to be silent about our convictions.

The conviction that you have in your heart is the foundation for any kind of courage you’re ever going to express. 

These convictions have to be grounded in God’s word. 

Start saying what you believe to be true, because being silent begets more silence.

We can trust God. 

God knows what He’s up to, He knows what He is doing. 

He can take what the enemy means for evil and turn it for good. 

So put your trust in him- and I can assure you He will never let you down.

Is the presence of God enough?

When life turns for the worse, are you comforted to know he is with you?

Throughout history the only worthy opponent to the power of chaos is the presence of God, all the way back to Genesis.

You can watch @faitheurycho’s full message ‘Comfort in Chaos’ at thinqmedia.com

We need to be motivated to bring the love of Christ into every broken system we encounter. 

Instead of being cynical and hopeless, we must bring optimism and expectation. 

Our focus needs to move from self to others; from problems to solutions; from failure to redemption; from brokenness to restoration. 

We must recognize the broken, weak, fallen, and corrupt and strive to not leave them in that condition-but be moved to change things. 

Above all we need to offer a new way forward-a way to act, live, and bring others along and into the new reality of how things ought to be.

How God created them to be.

We have to wake up.

Whether you are the pastor of a church, parent to the next generation, or thought leader of any capacity we need to be equipped and equip those around us for the heavy topics of todays culture.

We can’t shy away, and we need to be geared with the truth of scriptures and, in love, be ready to have these conversations.

Watch the whole interview ‘Navigating Cultural Chaos’ at thinqmedia.com

Cade never gave up.

After 20 attempts over the last 4 years to try to make our way up and wake surf we finally did it.

He remained persistent over these years.

Every time someone else would wake surf he would watch and point and say ‘I want to do it’ and we would jump in the water and we would try but we just could not get up.

And then today, we got up.

And we enjoyed 2 minutes of amazing joy.

#downsyndrome #downsyndromeawareness

Or when we miss conversations all together because we can’t look up from our phones?

They notice more than you think, and it affects them more than you know.

Your child’s future and wellbeing is much more important than the work email or YouTube video- trust me.

What are some of the ways we can be wise about preparing for a grid-down scenario?
 
No, a grid-down scenario in the U.S. is not a perfectly timed, festive holiday topic to consider. But that’s exactly the point. Such a scenario is unpredictable, yet not at all unexpected—for those who are paying attention.
 
Despite the fresh swirl around the topic prompted by the Netflix release, Leave the World Behind, the U.S. has long been vulnerable to cyber attacks and even worse—catastrophic Electromagnetic Pulse (EMP) attacks. 
 
Dr. William Forstchen, Professor of History at Montreat College and leading voice on EMPs, sat down with @gabelyons at THINQ Culture Summit last April to discuss how exposed America’s electrical infrastructure really is. 
 

Head to thinqmedia.com to watch the full talk and create conversations about how we as individuals and as the Church can best prepare. (Link in bio)

Comment "Sustainable" to see this full talk and a collection of others to help you become prepared.

What could really happen in a grid down scenario?

With the new Netflix release, “Leave the World Behind” people are beginning to see the reality of this threat.

Dr. William Forstchen predicts 90% of Americans would perish within 1-2 years. 

We don’t need to be fearful, but how can we be best prepared?

When we forget our identity is found in Christ it’s easy to become fearful of our circumstances, culture, or of the future.

Remember who you are and whose you are and in that you will find true peace.

One of my highlights from 2023 was attending the ARC forum hosted by Dr. Jordan Peterson, Philippa Stroud, Os Guinness and others.

Thousands of leaders gathered from across the globe in London to discuss the challenges of our time, the foundations of our civilizations, and the current future pathway we find ourselves on.

My main take away was that we need to lead. Our world is searching for something greater, for a purpose and peace greater than this world can offer.

As we enter the new year be encouraged, and go forward with boldness, equipped with the truth, and remembering who is in control.
We need the wisdom of the older generation and the enthusiasm of the younger generation.

You can’t have a functioning society if people are afraid or not allowed to tell the truth.
